I’ve tried so hard these last few years. You have too. We all have. And yet, no matter how hard I tried, I never got to the peak, crossed the finish line, or achieved the goal of “trying harder.” And that’s the problem. We never achieve the goal, because it’s not a goal, it’s a hamster wheel. Trying harder will keep you moving, wear you out, but won’t take you anywhere.
•
But what if instead of trying the same thing (only harder), we didn’t. What if we got off the hamster wheel of traditions, resolutions, and expectations, and tried something new instead?
•
What if you replaced the old attitude with a new approach? Maybe you would discover an open door that you thought was a dead end… Perhaps you would find a relationship you didn’t know you were looking for… Maybe you would get the answer to the prayer you had stopped praying.
•
I don’t know exactly what it looks like to get off that hamster wheel in 2023, but I’m hopeful, and hope feels like a really good place to start. I’ve learned that even when you don’t have the full solution, you can take the first step, and I’m determined to keep walking until I get to the solution. In the meantime, I’d love to know your thoughts.  Jump in the comments and let me know if you resonate with this and what you’re going to do differently in 2023. Save. Send. Sahara. 
•

‼️this new year word comes with a warning‼️
often I ask God to do something new in my life, but I forget to mention that I want it to look like the old thing. because old is comfortable, and old makes sense, and old feels like i’m “getting back to normal.” but just because something is old doesn’t mean it’s normal.
•
so while we keep looking for the new thing in old packaging, could we be missing the miracle because we won’t let go of the memory? and don’t get me wrong, the memory isn’t bad (in fact it may be beautiful) but it will blind us to the new if we can’t see past it.
•
is there a season of your life you keep trying to “get back to,” thinking things would be better if you could just get “back there”? are you still holding onto the way things used to be? are you waiting for someone who walked out of your life to walk back in? maybe it’s time to release your grip on the seasons, or methods, or people that are in the past. staying emotionally attached to the way things used to be may be the very thing preventing you from seeing how things could be. maybe it’s time to open your eyes and heart to the new… as one hamilton-y scholar once said, “look around, look around, how lucky we are to be alive right now.” don’t be afraid to take your eyes off the old… there’s a miracle right in front of you, here in the new.
•
“see, I am doing a new thing!
now it springs up, do you not perceive it?”
isaiah 43:19

Just because it’s a new year doesn’t mean we’re all feeling ready for it! If you’re like a lot of us, already feeling burnt out from your attempts to start all the new things or growing weary of what this year may or may not bring…THIS week’s podcast episode is for YOU!! 
✨
There is so much newness that comes with a new year: new goals, new missions, new resolutions — yet so often we find ourselves losing steam so quickly. We love pulling out the scriptures like Isaiah 43:19, praying for God to do a new thing. But what are we really asking God to do? Do we really mean it? Or are we actually praying for God to give us a new result without having to change the old method?🤯⚡️
✨
It’s the pep talk we all need to kick off 2023 in the right direction and avoid falling into the trap of overrated “new year, new me” mindsets. We promise you’ll leave  encouraged to vet out the old and narrow thinking and sincerely open your hands to the new things God is really doing. 🙌

🎧 Listen now on Spotify, Apple Podcast & Anchor: Anchor.fm/lightworkers

The miracles Jesus did were messy, spontaneous, and offensive to anyone who idolised their religious education over encountering a living Saviour. You know the worst part about that? It didn’t stop with the Pharisees. I have been that offended religious person too. I have been quick to criticise anything that didn’t fit my “Christian criteria,” because staying within the religious lines I had drawn around my faith made me feel safe. But I decided a while ago that I don’t want safe if it means that I miss what Jesus is doing. And I like having answers (correction: I love having answers), but I decided that I didn’t need all the answers if they were going to come at the expense of an experience with God. So I put down my religious ego and started searching for Jesus. And as I’ve been studying the miracles He did with my ClubDevotion community this month, I’m having an encounter with His miraculousness (let’s pretend that’s a word ok?) all over again.
❤️
And I don’t care that I have less answers and religious one liners to answer people than ever. Because you know what I do have? Experiences with Jesus. Even when I can’t always find the words to explain them. Testimonies of personal miracles. Even if it means I have to let go of control and trust Him to show up (and He always does). Conversations about how God is working, in real time, through anyone (literally anyone) who is saying yes to Jesus. And that might be my favourite one. If the only time you want to talk about Jesus is on a Sunday or in a “safe” environment with people who believe the exact same thing as you, it might be time to get unsafe.
❤️
People made the mistake once of undermining or overlooking miracles simply because they didn’t look like they thought they “should.” Let’s not make that same mistake again. Because the truth is… Miracles are happening everywhere. Right now. Unexpected. Unconventional. Holy. Miracles.
And I for one am determined to celebrate them, not criticise them.
❤️

We all want a miracle but we don’t want to actually NEED a miracle. 🫣 Meaning we want the extraordinary miracle story, but not the mess, crisis or struggle that comes before it. So what happens when we can’t find God when we’re in the tension of waiting on a miracle? 

Easter is the pinnacle of the ultimate miracle and it’s also a time we often reflect on the reality of our faith. Do I really trust God? Does he really do miracles in my life? Why won’t he answer my prayers? (the way we THINK it should be answered 👀)

Instead of running away from these big questions we’re running straight towards them. 🏃‍♀️💨This Easter we want to get real with you guys, about when faith became real to us…and spoiler alert: it rarely comes in the pretty package we expect. But it’s the beautiful, broken and messy reality where God meets us with the biggest and brightest miracles that make faith what it is. 🙏💛

These next episodes of On a Lighter Note leading up to Easter we are going to be diving into the miraculous experiences and stories that made the story of Jesus real to you. And in usual fashion..I’ll go first. 

Listen to this new episode AVAILABLE NOW! “When You Want the Miracle but Not the Mess” 🙏 On Apple Podcasts, Spotify and Anchor 

#OnaLighterNote #Podcast

Let’s not sleep on the reality of this word right here and its relevance to you RIGHT NOW. @pastorsamuelrodriguez reminds us today on our latest episode of On a Lighter Note. 

We all have messes we’re asking God for help from. While we’d like to constantly be on fire with hope— we know with time, disappointments, traumas we can become spiritually blinded… When we can’t “see” God’s hand in the physical — we start to doubt his work in the spiritual. 

Jesus knew exactly how to speak to our souls for this exact situation and he did it by doing the unexpected, by using the very mess we’re so defeated or feel bound by — to turn his miracles. 

We have an absolute fire hydrant of straight up knowledge wisdom and POWER from the one and only @pastorsamuelrodriguez - who is here to profess what God has boldly proclaimed over our mess 🗣️ “THE BATTLE HAS ALREADY BEEN WON” 🔥🔥🔥

In his latest book “Your Mess, God's Miracle: The Process Is Temporary, the Promise Is Permanent” — he guides us through the scriptural evidence that God is ALWAYS working no matter what our state of mind, body and heart my understand at the time.

To start Easter week… What about Mrs. Pilate?!
♡
A lot of people know Pontius pilate, the guy that ultimately sentenced Jesus to death, but tried not to take the blame for it… but you know who we don’t talk about? Mrs Pilate.
We don’t hear her name, but we do hear her voice, and I think we have a lot to learn.
♡
So for the moments you took a step of obedience but it didn’t effect the outcome… And the times you used your voice but they didn’t listen… And even if you’re watching this right now, feeling like you failed… I just want to remind you (and so does she)… You can’t see the whole story. Obedience matters, even when we can’t see the outcome.
♡
Comment if this spoke to you; and let’s spread the word. Love you! Mean it! 🤍
#easter

I relate to getting mad at inanimate objects. One time I cussed out a patch of grass that I tripped over during a run. I’m not saying I’m proud of my behaviour; I’m just saying I relate. But that’s not what’s happening here. Jesus wasn’t hangry, or bored, or looking for a random tree to blame.
♡
So what’s the reason behind a figless fig tree being cursed by the One who created it? I don’t completely know, but this is my working theory… Because it’s never just about the tree.
♡
Maybe it’s time to embrace who we really are. No filters. No leaves. Just us.
♡
Comment if this spoke to you; and let’s spread the word. Love you! Mean it! 🤍

It was a moment of true worship by a woman who couldn't possibly
understand its significance. All she knew was that Jesus was worth it.
Worth the price. 
Worth the sacrifice. 
Worth being misunderstood, 
even by those who believed the same thing. But I guess once you've experienced extra grace, you can't help but overflow with extra gratitude.
♡ 
And because she didn't weaken her worship for those that didn't understand it, Jesus defended her in front of them.
♡ 
What's your perfume jar? What's the thing you invested your time and
money and worth in? When you allow that thing to break open at Jesus

If you don’t think social media has ever brought out an ugly side of you, like ever? Then you’re probably lying… and that’s not great either. If we’re honest (which is a good thing to be), it can bring out the worst in ALL of us. Whether it’s clapping back with mean one liners in the comments, laughing at the latest “internet drag,” or consuming online fights like popcorn —  we’ve all played a part of cancel culture in some form, but it’s now expanded into what feels like bully culture. Everything is reactionary, everything is graceless, and no one is at fault except those we decide are “canceled.”
•
Before you say it’s not a real thing, it is, and it’s exactly what happened to my guest on todays podcast, my newest soul sister Brittany Dawn. 
•
Brittany has walked the public approval tight rope and has been at the center of some of social media’s most beautiful, and ugliest sides. Today, we are going past the screens and usernames and are talking straight to the heart of the person.. yes, even her keyboard warriors. How do we navigate the constant comparison that happens when scrolling through highlight reels? How do we stop ourselves from using hate to combat hate online? What does life look like after you’ve been deemed “canceled”? 
•
Through vulnerability and sharing both our stories, I pray we might all lay down our keyboard weapons, confront our skeletons, and respond with speaking life instead of labels. It’s hard work, but it’s good work, and it’s never been more needed. 
•
Don’t miss this incredible episode of On a Lighter Note “Living on the Tight Rope of Cancel Culture” with Brittany Dawn.

But it doesn’t matter if you don’t believe it.

At some point you have to decide that you’ve done all the work, you’ve prepared all you can, and what’s left is to give it a shot. 

Because it’s time. Time to step out, to say yes, to trust your own preparedness. After all, that’s what your whole last season has been about. God has been preparing you for this. But it won’t matter if you keep making excuses.

And you’ll find them anywhere, the excuses. You’ll find reasons to discount yourself if you look for them. You’ll find signs that this won’t work if you look for them. You’ll find people to justify you staying here (when you know you’re supposed to go there). You’ll find ways to procrastinate. You’ll find roads that leads away from the one you know you’re supposed to be on. You’ll find whatever you keep looking for. It won’t change all the work you’ve put in, but it will determine whether your work was worth it… or wasted. 

So I guess the real question is… Do you trust yourself?

I can tell you that you’re ready, but it won’t matter if you don’t believe it. You have to trust in the work you’ve done. Trust your preparedness. Trust that God has gone before you. Trust that you are covered. Trust that it’s going to work out. Trust that He will tell you to go right or left. Trust that you are ready.

And then do something about it.

‼️Would You Rather: Peace or Understanding?‼️
Ever played Would You Rather with someone who cannot just give you ONE answer?? They have to ask clarifying questions, add qualifiers, and argue over a scenario that doesn’t exist… it starts feeling less like a game and more like you’re on trial in a courtroom! But Paul isn’t doing that in this verse. He’s giving us two options, and then telling us the answer. Our human nature craves understanding, answers, and clarity… But I think that’s because we think that’s the only path to peace. 
•
What if (even just for today), we lay down our need for answers long enough to accept His peace? I think we’d find that the path to peace isn’t understanding, it’s Jesus. 
•
I’m praying peace over every person who watches this today. Let me know in the comments where you need peace today. Send it to someone who needs it. Save it for the next time you do. 
•
He’s got the whole world in His hands. And that includes your world. And that means you don’t have to carry it. Hand it over. Receive peace. In Jesus name.
•
Love you. Mean it. 
•
Philippians 4:6-7 (AMP)
Do not be anxious or worried about anything, but in everything [every circumstance and situation] by prayer and petition with thanksgiving, continue to make your [specific] requests known to God. And the peace of God [that peace which reassures the heart, that peace] which transcends all understanding, [that peace which] stands guard over your hearts and your minds in Christ Jesus [is yours].

I will spend the rest of my life telling people that their scars tell a story, and it is not a story of defeat. And the reason it’s my life message is because it has been my life experience.

No one’s life is exactly as it is fed to us in this feed. Everyone is walking through something that can’t be put in a caption or captured on a reel. But spend a day with any human still breathing and you will soon realise that the scars that you don’t see when you scroll are real for us all. They just happen in between the posts and behind the phone. So can we be honest about them, instead of pretending that the lessons we’ve learned didn’t require blood, sweat, and more tears than we knew we had in us??

My math teacher used to mark me down for not “showing my work.” Turns out that I could submit the correct answer but still miss the point. Sometimes we do that. We share our stories and experiences with other people like it’s a ted talk. But people don’t need to hear another speech full of alliteration but void of authenticity. They need to see scars from someone who made it through. Your scars prove that your answer is authentic. And it’s shows someone walking through the same thing, that they can make it too. 

If Jacob kept walking even with his limp, you can too. If Paul kept preaching even with his thorn, you can too. And if Jesus kept showing up with his scars to offer people salvation, you can too. 

So.. I don’t know who told you that you had to hide your scars.. But Jesus didn’t. Jesus used His scars to tell a bigger story — a story of love, forgiveness, and redemption. L And if it’s good enough for Jesus? It’s good enough for you and me. What do you think? 🤍

Back in the day, I used to lead worship. Honestly, I’m pretty sure every pastors kid had to sing in the church choir at least once— probably some kind of PK initiation. But growing up, I loved singing. I still do. But when I started preaching more at the church I was serving at the time, a pastor told me that I needed to choose between worship leading or preaching. She told me that if I wanted to do both, it would be a sign to her that I wanted attention, and that meant I had pride. Immediately, I stopped. I hated the thought of not singing anymore, but I hated the thought of being prideful more.

NOTE: Pastors, please be careful not to project your own insecurities onto your young people and make it sound spiritual.. they might just believe you.

Looking back, I know that person was wrong. But it took a lot of years, great therapy, and theological discipleship to correct that one pastors flippant comment.

I’m telling you this story, not to vent, and I pray that isn’t the vibe of this. I’m posting it so that maybe someone reading who has believed that their gift was only useful in a specific setting, or for a specific gender, or as an assistant to someone else, or for a past season, would realise that it’s a lie. It’s not truth and it did not come God.

Are there times to use a skill in a specific setting? You bet. Are there times God asks us to lay a gift aside for a season? I believe so. But do you have to limit the way God created you to fit the human culture around you? Absolutely not. 

Don’t you dare shrink yourself or your God just because of some small thinking around you. (I say that in love, so read it in your head with my accent, it will soften it 😘)

Think bigger. Go deeper. Rise higher. And watch God break you out of the box that He was never confined to in the first place.

‭‭2 Corinthians‬ ‭6‬:‭11‬-‭13‬ 
“I can’t tell you how much I long for you to enter this wide-open, spacious life. We didn’t fence you in. The smallness you feel comes from within you. Your lives aren’t small, but you’re living them in a small way. I’m speaking as plainly as I can and with great affection. Open up your lives. Live openly and expansively!”

We don’t need God to tell us all of the details! 🕊️

Just some thoughts from me (a novice),
For you (anyone who is interested).

For anyone in the middle of an honest fight with God… For those wrestling for their identity, for their future, for their blessing… This is for you. 

Hang in there. Don’t loosen your grip or weaken your grit now… The blessing is coming. And I know you’re tired, and I know you’re anxious, but you’ve come too far to quit now. And yeah, you might walk with a limp after this, but you can do a lot with a limp. Just ask Jacob.

You’ll come out of this season having dealt with your past. You’ll see old problems with new vision.
You’ll be a brand new you.

So don’t give up now. Hang in there. The wrestle you’ve been in is about to turn into an embrace. And you’ll have the blessing to prove it.

Genesis 32:26 “I will not let you go until you bless me.”

Get this… In Genesis 27 there’s these two brothers - Jacob and Esau. Esau was the oldest and he was in line to get the blessing from his dad (Isaac). The problem was, Jacob was a mama’s boy, and she convinced him to deceive Isaac so he could get the blessing instead. So he did.. Because like I said, mama’s boy. He pretended to be his brother (his dad was blind), deceived his dad, and manipulated the blessing that should have been Esau’s… And ya, Esau was not happy. And ya, that’s an understatement. Esau begged his dad for another blessing, but the blessing was more like back handed compliment, because Isaac told Esau he wouldn’t be free until he decided to break free from his offense. So often we think that holding onto the past or person who hurt us is freedom, but it’s only keeping us chained.

Your freedom is your decision. When you decide to break free, you will be free. So I don’t know what happened to you, what words were spoken over you, or the people who abandoned you… I just  know that in this bible story, these words aren’t just for Esau - they are for you and me. Your decision to break free is not saying that what they did was right, it’s a declaration that your freedom is more important than your offense.

It’s time. What do you need to break free from today? It’s time to decide… But it’s your call.

I felt sentimental the other day so I wrote this, to remind myself that of all the things that haven’t turned out like I thought, I am forever grateful God saw to it to make sure this thing has.

Since I was a little girl, I wanted to preach.
A lot of things in my life haven’t turned out like I expected them to, for example: I did not become Judge Judy’s successor, I did not get headhunted to guest star in 7th Heaven, and I am yet to find my person. 
A lot of my life hasn’t happened like I daydreamed it might.

But since I was a little girl, I wanted to preach. 
I wanted to craft sermons that made people laugh, 
share stories that made people feel seen, 
and tell people they were created by a God who was, is, 
and always will be madly in love with them.

And you know what? 
Somewhere inside my big, too sensitive heart, 
I knew that I would. 

I knew I would spend my time, talent, and facial expressions telling people how much Jesus loves them, showing them how cool the Bible is, and letting them know that shame is a liar. 

Since I was a little girl, I wanted to preach. 
So I prayed that I would, 
I prepared so I could, 
and now that I do?? 

I never want to take for granted the gift that God has given me, or the responsibility He has entrusted  to me. And I never want to forget how proud that little girl would be. 

I also never want to forgot how loved I am by God before I do any of it. 

Since I was a little girl, I wanted to preach.
I hope when I am an old girl, I am still preaching.

God doesn’t tie up our loose ends, He ties them all into your story. When I had this revelation about the context of Jeremiah 29:11, it changed everything for me. And I pray it does for you too. Let me know. 🤍🙏🏼

At the start of this year, January 24th to be exact, I was pretty heartbroken. I was asking where God was, if He was listening, and why the things He had promised me were taking so long. I was running on borrowed hope and feeling exhausted by a life that looked so much different than I thought it would. 

My friend @dawn_marraccino sent me a podcast of @miafieldes telling her story about holding onto faith in Gods promise to her, even when nothing seemed to change. I decided I was going to do the same. My best friend @katy__knox and I drove down to the beach, walked down to this life guard stand, and started to pray. We made a promise that we were going to keep coming here.. Keep showing up… To pray… To remind God what He promised. To remind ourselves that it was coming. And just like Mia, we ran around the stand like it was the walls of Jericho, like we were super spiritual Christians, like we actually believed that God was good for His word. And we did. 

Somewhere along the way, I started to believe it again. I started to remember how God had been faithful, to believe that if He promised it, He was going to do it. And this isn’t a post to tell you that God has answered my prayers. I’m still in the waiting. But I think that’s what makes it even more special. 

So often we post the things after the promise has come. But what if we could be grateful today for the miracle that’s on the way? For the promise we don’t have a photo of, because it hasn’t happened just yet? After all, our job isn’t to make a miracle happen, our job is to keep our hopes up and our hearts open to it. To thank God before we have a reason to. To cling to hope like oxygen, especially in seasons of suffocating grief.  That’s where our faith is tested. That’s where His grace is felt. 

And so today, I’m grateful. I’m so, so grateful. Not because I have a promise to post, but because I have more belief for it than ever. I’m grateful to a God who sees my pain, a God who hears my prayers, and a God who makes good on His promises. Happy Thanksgiving fam. Love you. Mean it. 🤍

So maybe things seem dark right now, maybe it feels like there is a void in your life, or like everyone else is seeing things happen and you’re staring at nothing… But I want to remind you… God hovers in the dark, then He speaks to it, and commands there to be light. You might just be in verse two. But take heart sweet one, verse three is coming next, and that’s where the light arrives.

Genesis 1:2-3 “Now the earth was formless and empty, darkness was over the surface of the deep, and the Spirit of God was hovering over the waters.” And God said, “Let there be light.” And there was light.”
